responded: The root cause of the bug is that `FreeList<T>::IsUsed(Index index)` does not check if `index` is within the bounds of `list_`. If an out-of-bounds index is passed, it will access invalid memory, causing a segmentation fault. This is confirmed by the sanitizer report and the code:

```cpp
bool FreeList<T>::IsUsed(Index index) const {
  return (reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(list_[index]) & ptrFreeBit) == 0;
}
```

There is no bounds check on `index`. The same applies to `Store::IsValid(Ref ref)`:

```cpp
inline bool Store::IsValid(Ref ref) const {
  return objects_.IsUsed(ref.index) && objects_.Get(ref.index);
}
```

If `ref.index` is out of bounds, this will crash.

**Patch Plan:**
- Add a bounds check in `FreeList<T>::IsUsed(Index index) const` to ensure `index < list_.size()`.
- This will make `Store::IsValid` and all other users of `IsUsed` safe.

